issue.title: Document CLI keyring storage for session tokens
issue.body:
## Description

Add documentation about the CLI's new keyring-based session token storage to `docs/admin/users/sessions-tokens.md` and related pages.

As of v2.29.0, the Coder CLI now stores session tokens in the operating system keyring by default (on macOS and Windows) instead of storing them in plain text files. This is a significant security improvement that affects how users authenticate with the CLI, but it's not currently documented in the session/token documentation.

**Pages to update:**
- `docs/admin/users/sessions-tokens.md` - Add a section explaining keyring storage
- `docs/install/cli.md` - Mention keyring storage in CLI authentication section (if appropriate)
- Potentially add troubleshooting guidance for users experiencing keyring issues

**Key information to include:**
- Default behavior: tokens stored in OS keyring on macOS/Windows (enabled by default as of v2.29.0)
- How to opt-out: Use `--use-keyring=false` flag
- Environment variable: `CODER_USE_KEYRING`
- When file-based storage is used: when `--global-config` is set, or on platforms without keyring support
- Security benefits of keyring storage over plain text files
- Migration note: existing plain text tokens will be migrated on next login

## Impact

Users upgrading to v2.29.0+ may not understand why their session token storage location changed or how to troubleshoot keyring-related issues. Admins need to know about this security improvement when planning upgrades and supporting users.

## Links

- Breaking change in v2.29.0: https://github.com/coder/coder/releases/tag/v2.29.0
- Related PR: #20256, #20613, #20851
- CLI reference already documents `--use-keyring` flag: https://coder.com/docs/reference/cli

issue.title: Document OpenTelemetry tracing configuration and capabilities
issue.body:
## Description

Create comprehensive documentation for Coder's OpenTelemetry tracing feature in the monitoring section (`/docs/admin/monitoring/`). While AI Bridge-specific tracing is documented in `/docs/ai-coder/ai-bridge/monitoring.md`, there's no general documentation about tracing for the Coder server and its capabilities.

The documentation should cover:

1. **What is traced**: Overview of what operations/components support tracing in Coder
2. **Configuration**: How to enable tracing using `--trace` flag or `CODER_TRACE_ENABLE` environment variable
3. **Exporting traces**: Configuration for trace exporters (currently Honeycomb via `--trace-honeycomb-api-key` is available)
4. **Trace logs integration**: Document `--trace-logs` flag and its cost/volume implications
5. **Use cases**: When to use tracing for debugging, performance analysis, and troubleshooting
6. **Best practices**: Recommendations for production usage, sampling strategies, and managing trace volume

**Suggested location**: Create new `/docs/admin/monitoring/tracing.md` and add it to the monitoring index page

**Related features documented**:
- AI Bridge tracing is already documented in AI Bridge monitoring docs (added in PR #21106)
- CLI flags are documented in the server reference but lack usage guidance

## Impact

Without comprehensive tracing documentation:
- Administrators may not know that OpenTelemetry tracing is available as a debugging and monitoring tool
- Users won't understand how to configure and use tracing effectively for troubleshooting
- The relationship between server-wide tracing and AI Bridge-specific traces isn't clear
- Cost and performance implications of enabling trace logs aren't well understood

## Links

- PR that added AI Bridge tracing: https://github.com/coder/coder/pull/21106
- AI Bridge monitoring docs (has tracing section): https://github.com/coder/coder/blob/main/docs/ai-coder/ai-bridge/monitoring.md#tracing

issue.title: Document sub-agent behavior during devcontainer rebuilds and workspace health
issue.body:
## Description

Document the behavior of sub-agents during devcontainer rebuilds and how they affect workspace health status in the devcontainers documentation (likely in `/docs/user-guides/workspace-lifecycle.md` or the new devcontainer docs being prepared in #21080).

As of PR #21098, sub-agents are now excluded from workspace health calculations. This prevents workspaces from showing as "unhealthy" when a devcontainer rebuilds and its sub-agent temporarily disconnects. Users should understand:

1. **What happens during a devcontainer rebuild**: The sub-agent temporarily disconnects while the container is being rebuilt
2. **Health status behavior**: The workspace will remain showing as "healthy" during devcontainer rebuilds because sub-agents don't affect workspace health
3. **Why this matters**: Previously, devcontainer rebuilds would cause the entire workspace to appear unhealthy, which was confusing to users

This should be documented in context with other devcontainer lifecycle information so users understand what to expect when rebuilding their devcontainers.

## Impact

Users need to understand workspace health behavior when using devcontainers to avoid confusion during rebuilds. Without documentation:
- Users may be uncertain whether their workspace is actually healthy during a devcontainer rebuild
- Support questions may arise about why health status behaves differently with devcontainers
- Users may not understand the relationship between sub-agents and workspace health

## Links

- PR that changed behavior: https://github.com/coder/coder/pull/21098
- Related devcontainer docs rewrite (in progress): https://github.com/coder/coder/pull/21080
- Thread where this request originated: https://codercom.slack.com/archives/D0A1DVC2B8S/p1764888926119129
